{
  "texts": [
    "Although RNNs excel at capturing temporal dependencies, they also have limitations in stock price prediction.",
    "For example, RNNs struggle with highly volatile or noisy data, which is common in stock prices, potentially leading to over-fitting or reduced accuracy.Currently, due to its outstanding performance in sequential tasks, Transformer becomes a popular candidate in stock price prediction [24][25][26].",
    "The Transformer model, proposed by [27], is a deep learning architecture widely used in natural language processing (NLP) and other sequential tasks, including time series forecasting.",
    "For example, some Transformer-based models have been shown to be able to outperform some classical models such as LSTM in stock price prediction [28][29][30].However, most existing Transformer-based models in finance focus solely on the target company's own historical data or sentiment [31], overlooking the influence of other related companies such as competitors, suppliers, or strategic partners.",
    "Although Transformers excel at capturing temporal dependencies within a single input sequence, they are not explicitly designed to model inter-company sentiment relationships."
  ]
}